ized": false, "mention": "17&beta;-trenbolone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9993269443511963, "span": {"begin": 1072, "end": 1091}}, {"id": ["mesh:D004997"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "17alpha-ethynylestradiol", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9991216659545898, "span": {"begin": 1102, "end": 1126}}, {"id": ["mesh:D004967"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "estrogen", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9995654225349426, "span": {"begin": 1224, "end": 1232}}, {"id": ["mesh:D008777"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "methyltestosterone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9995274543762207, "span": {"begin": 1282, "end": 1300}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:7955"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "zebrafish", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9814513325691223, "span": {"begin": 1341, "end": 1350}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "fathead minnows", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.8746370077133179, "span": {"begin": 1352, "end": 1367}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:90988"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Pimephales promelas", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.967146098613739, "span": {"begin": 1369, "end": 1388}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:8090"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Japanese medaka", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.967095136642456, "span": {"begin": 1400, "end": 1415}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:8090"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Oryzias latipes", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9818783402442932, "span": {"begin": 1417, "end": 1432}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:7955"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "zebrafish", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9145283102989197, "span": {"begin": 1506, "end": 1515}}, {"id": ["mesh:D013196"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "dihydrotestosterone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9986425042152405, "span": {"begin": 1519, "end": 1538}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:367", "231", "2232"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "AR", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 1554, "end": 1556}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:74940"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Chinook salmon", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9282432794570923, "span": {"begin": 1735, "end": 1749}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:74940"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Oncorhynchus tshawytscha", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9806454181671143, "span": {"begin": 1751, "end": 1775}}, {"id": ["mesh:D000728"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "androgens", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9987978935241699, "span": {"begin": 1822, "end": 1831}}, {"id": ["mesh:D008777"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "methyltestosterone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9998694658279419, "span": {"begin": 1833, "end": 1851}}, {"id": ["mesh:C008376"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "methyldihydrotestosterone and 11-ketotestosterone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.954734206199646, "span": {"begin": 1853, "end": 1902}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:7998"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Ictalurus punctatus", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9289785027503967, "span": {"begin": 2128, "end": 2147}}, {"id": ["mesh:D014204"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "trenbolone acetate", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9990111589431763, "span": {"begin": 2179, "end": 2197}}], "text": "There have been several studies with teleost fish exposed to known androgen receptor agonists during early development that have documented a consequent occurrence of male-biased sex ratios.    Exposure of fish to androgens during early development has been used as a technique to preferentially produce male-biased populations in aquaculture for decades. Pandian and Sheela (1995) provided a comprehensive overview of effects of hormones on sex inversion in the context of aquacultural&nbsp;practices. They reported, for example, that the synthetic androgen&nbsp;17alpha-methyltestosterone had been used to successfully produce male-biased sex ratios in 25 different teleost&nbsp;species.&nbsp;&nbsp;  Controlled expoure of zebrafish (Danio rerio) to the synthetic androgen&nbsp;17&beta;-trenbolone during development has been shown to result&nbsp;in male biased sex ratios (Holbech et al., 2006; Orn et al., 2006; Larsen &amp; Baatrup, 2010; Morthorst et al., 2010; Baumann et al., 2013, 2015; Golan &amp; Levavi-Sivian 2014). Zebrafish studies using binary mixtures of 17&beta;-trenbolone with&nbsp;17alpha-ethynylestradiol administered via the water&nbsp;also&nbsp;reported an elevated occurrence of males even when the estrogen was present&nbsp;(Orn et al., 2016)  Exposure to methyltestosterone resulted in male biased cohorts in&nbsp;zebrafish, fathead minnows (Pimephales promelas), and&nbsp;Japanese medaka (Oryzias latipes) (Bogers et al., 2006; Orn et al., 2003; Seki et al., 2004)  Exposure of zebrafish to dihydrotestosterone, an endogenous AR agonist,&nbsp;during early development reulted in&nbsp;a male biased sex ratio (Baumann et al., 2013; Shi et al., 2018).  Two-hour immersion of newly hatched, homogametic female Chinook salmon (Oncorhynchus tshawytscha) in&nbsp;different synthetic and natural&nbsp;androgens (methyltestosterone, methyldihydrotestosterone and 11-ketotestosterone) reulted in&nbsp;a concentration dependent increase in male sex ratio in the treated fish&nbsp;(Piferrer &amp; Donaldson, 1993)  A concentration-dependent increase in percentage of males was observed in channel catfish&nbsp;(Ictalurus punctatus) that were orally administered trenbolone acetate for 60 days starting with swim-up fry (Galvez et al., 1995)", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:31:54 +0000 2026"}